{\"video_title\":\"Writing Effective Few-Shot Examples\",\"transcript\":\"вЂ‹Let's look at some examples of where we're вЂ‹making mistakes in our few-shot examples. вЂ‹Things that we can do wrong in вЂ‹the formatting of our prompts and вЂ‹what we can think about and learn from these examples. вЂ‹Here's some few-shot examples. вЂ‹The idea behind this is we put together вЂ‹a not very good prompt to analyze how hard things are, вЂ‹like is it soft or hard? вЂ‹That's really what we're trying to get at вЂ‹with this prompt and some few-shot examples. вЂ‹Now this is not a good prompt. вЂ‹This is a bad prompt and we'll see why. вЂ‹What we've got is we have input, вЂ‹as the prefix, we then got brick. вЂ‹We've got output as a prefix and then hard. вЂ‹We've got input as a prefix and then pillow, output soft. вЂ‹Then we've got input car. вЂ‹Now, notice what we've got here. вЂ‹One, we don't have a lot of examples here, but two, вЂ‹we've switched gears, вЂ‹we started talking about вЂ‹input and output and the hardness of вЂ‹things using things that are really obvious, probably. вЂ‹A brick is hard, вЂ‹a pillow is soft, вЂ‹I guess car is hard but it's not вЂ‹as clear what we're getting at. вЂ‹We also might just be trying to describe вЂ‹some fundamental intrinsic capability вЂ‹or properties of this thing. вЂ‹It may not be about hard or вЂ‹soft because it could be other things. вЂ‹It could just be an attribute to вЂ‹describe the thing itself вЂ‹because pillows are generally thought of вЂ‹as soft and bricks are normally thought of as hard, вЂ‹those are fundamental descriptors вЂ‹sometimes they use for them. вЂ‹What we see is that when we вЂ‹prompt ChatGPT in this example, вЂ‹what we get is, it says, вЂ‹fast or maybe transportation. вЂ‹This shows us a couple of things. вЂ‹This is a prompt that's not very вЂ‹well-designed and because of that, вЂ‹what we see is that ChatGPT isn't quite sure what вЂ‹the next output should be from the pattern. вЂ‹Now there's a couple of mistakes in here. вЂ‹One is we've got input and output. вЂ‹Input and output are really generic prefixes. вЂ‹They don't really give the language model вЂ‹much information about what вЂ‹the task is that it's trying to do. вЂ‹All we know is we're taking in вЂ‹something and we're getting out something, вЂ‹but it's not really telling вЂ‹us what it is that we're describing. вЂ‹Maybe we should go and say input, вЂ‹brick, surface feeling, hard, вЂ‹input, pillow, вЂ‹surface feeling, soft вЂ‹or maybe it's something about if you hit it, вЂ‹what will it feel like? вЂ‹There's all kinds of things we could do to give it вЂ‹more context around what we're trying to get at. вЂ‹We can also give it more examples. вЂ‹But what we've got here overall in вЂ‹this prompt is we've got a lack of information. вЂ‹It's not detailed enough and we're not вЂ‹giving enough information about what the task вЂ‹is that's being solved and the result of that is that вЂ‹the language model isn't really вЂ‹sure what the solution is. вЂ‹Now one way we can solve this вЂ‹is we can go and before we give our examples, вЂ‹we could give a little bit more context, вЂ‹so we can provide some instructions. вЂ‹We could say your output can only be soft or hard. вЂ‹Now, one thing to note is as I'm вЂ‹putting these things in quotation marks to try вЂ‹to indicate to the language model вЂ‹that these are the two values, вЂ‹I don't want it to get confused and think I'm talking вЂ‹about soft or hard in some other contexts, вЂ‹but I'm putting these things in quotation marks, вЂ‹giving them some emphasis that either it's soft or hard. вЂ‹This may not always work because we still have вЂ‹a prompt that's really generic. вЂ‹That really doesn't have вЂ‹a lot of context and a lot of meat to it. вЂ‹It's still very vague. вЂ‹We've got input brick, вЂ‹we're still dealing with it. вЂ‹Now luckily in this case, вЂ‹adding this little bit of additional context вЂ‹and specify to the language model that we only вЂ‹want soft or hard as an output helps it figure вЂ‹out that it should think about if I pushed on this car, вЂ‹how would it feel like, it would feel hard. вЂ‹That's the task that's being вЂ‹solved and so it comes back with the right thing. вЂ‹But that's our first thing to think about, вЂ‹when you're writing few-shot examples, вЂ‹are your examples detailed enough? вЂ‹Are your prefixes that you're вЂ‹using for these things meaningful? вЂ‹Do they give additional contexts that вЂ‹the large language model can use to вЂ‹figure out what the next thing in the sequence is. вЂ‹Another way to think about it is, вЂ‹if you gave this to 10 different human beings, вЂ‹would you have a chance of a few of them might be вЂ‹confused about what you're trying to ask for? вЂ‹If the answer is yes, вЂ‹then you probably need to think вЂ‹about how to refine your prompt. вЂ‹If it's not fully clear what you're trying to вЂ‹do in the examples of what вЂ‹the process behind the examples is illustrating, вЂ‹then you're probably not detailed enough. вЂ‹Now one way you can solve that is by adding вЂ‹some more instruction like вЂ‹we have here at the top of this prompt. вЂ‹Now let's look at another example. вЂ‹I've got object plane speed fast, вЂ‹object worm speeds slow вЂ‹and I go through a series of examples. вЂ‹Notice I'm giving a little bit more context here. вЂ‹My speed prefixes a little better вЂ‹because speed seems something that's quantifiable. вЂ‹Like a plane is fast. вЂ‹A worm is slow that should be more contexts. вЂ‹We then go prompt it with object ball speed вЂ‹and this is another important thing вЂ‹to realize is it says variable. вЂ‹One of the things we have to think about is we're trying вЂ‹to get the large language model to вЂ‹produce an output or to вЂ‹classify or to fit into some boxes. вЂ‹We need to make sure that it gets enough information in вЂ‹the input to be able to вЂ‹accurately put things into the boxes. вЂ‹We need to make sure that вЂ‹whatever information we're giving вЂ‹it about what it's going to do, вЂ‹always has enough context вЂ‹that it can make a decision about the label. вЂ‹Now in this case, a ball could be fast, it can be slow. вЂ‹If I shoot a ball out of вЂ‹a candidate might be going really fast. вЂ‹If I shoot a ball, вЂ‹if I put it on the top of a rocket, вЂ‹it might be going really fast. вЂ‹There's all different things that could вЂ‹make a ball go faster or slower. вЂ‹We have to make sure that we provide enough context. вЂ‹Now, in general, the thing to think вЂ‹about is am I given enough information? вЂ‹Now I'm going to go back. I'm going вЂ‹to change my prompt down. вЂ‹I'm going to say object ball kicked by a baby. вЂ‹Then we get immediately it says slow. вЂ‹When you're building up the few-shot examples, вЂ‹so you want to make sure one, вЂ‹your prefixes are pretty descriptive. вЂ‹Two, do the examples that you're giving, вЂ‹really give enough information вЂ‹to derive what the underlying processes that вЂ‹is going on in order to go from вЂ‹the starting input to the final output. вЂ‹Do you really have вЂ‹enough information there to вЂ‹see what's underneath the hood? вЂ‹One way to think about that is вЂ‹if you asked a bunch of humans, вЂ‹would they all know exactly what you wanted it to вЂ‹do without any ambiguity. вЂ‹Two, you want to make sure that you have вЂ‹enough description before the examples if вЂ‹needed to provide additional context. вЂ‹Sometimes examples, you're just вЂ‹not going to be able to get there with examples. вЂ‹You may need to provide some additional rules or вЂ‹other information at the start вЂ‹of your prompt to help it along. вЂ‹Really a lot of times what you're thinking вЂ‹about is you have a limited amount of space вЂ‹in your prompt and you have to think вЂ‹about is this something that I can вЂ‹better describe and an example вЂ‹or is it something that I can better вЂ‹describe in some instructions at the top? вЂ‹What better means is will вЂ‹it get a more accurate output and вЂ‹will it take less space вЂ‹or maybe less words to describe it? вЂ‹If I can get it done very clearly in an example, вЂ‹then maybe that's the right way to go. вЂ‹That example doesn't take a lot of space. вЂ‹On the other hand, вЂ‹if it's a really simple rule and I can describe it, вЂ‹I may be able to get a better response вЂ‹by putting that rule up into the description. вЂ‹Then finally, we have to make sure вЂ‹that we provide enough information. вЂ‹In this example, ball kicked by baby, вЂ‹if we're trying to ball kick вЂ‹things or we're trying to get a particular output, вЂ‹we may have to make sure that when we give вЂ‹input that there's sufficient richness and вЂ‹detail in that input to follow вЂ‹the rules or a prior examples that we've given. вЂ‹Now this is particularly important if вЂ‹our prior examples were pretty clear cut, вЂ‹is probably something better. вЂ‹Now, one could argue that our prior examples, вЂ‹if we go back and look at this, вЂ‹we said a plane was fast. вЂ‹Well, a plane might not be fast, вЂ‹a plane might be slow. вЂ‹It might be sitting parked on the tarmac of an airport. вЂ‹We also want to make sure that our examples вЂ‹are rich enough and detailed enough. вЂ‹Now sometimes we can get вЂ‹away with simple things like plane, вЂ‹fast, worm, slow in order to teach it. вЂ‹But sometimes we're going to have to go into more detail. вЂ‹We're going to provide more context. вЂ‹Make sure and think about, вЂ‹do you have enough real information? вЂ‹Is it going to depend on the situation, вЂ‹those things like that provide details. вЂ‹Now one way to do it would be to вЂ‹say just make some assumptions. вЂ‹But one of the things that can вЂ‹happen sometimes when you do вЂ‹that is you may get more verbose output, вЂ‹then you really want, it may not fit into that bucket. вЂ‹But when you're writing these prompts, вЂ‹think meaningfully about what is a meaningful prefix? вЂ‹What information or instructions do вЂ‹I need to have at the top and can вЂ‹important information be better вЂ‹conveyed as an instruction at the top or as an example? вЂ‹Do my examples cover the space enough to have вЂ‹enough good examples with rich detail for it вЂ‹to learn from and derive what the underlying process is? вЂ‹Then when I go and I give it the new input, вЂ‹do I make sure I have вЂ‹enough relevant contexts and information with вЂ‹the new input in order вЂ‹to apply the process that I taught? вЂ‹Because we may teach it the process really well, вЂ‹but then given a new input that just fundamentally вЂ‹is missing information in order to apply that process.\"} \n